</caption>
<paragraph id="C82B36D8DC11FF17FF171857FD4EDB0D" blockId="2.[166,1225,1635,1854]" lastBlockId="3.[174,1233,175,874]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="20" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">
D e s c r i p t i o n. Length: 1.6 mm. Slender, parallel-sided; color brownish-piceus (
<figureCitation id="50AF2A5DDC11FF16FF6218B0FFDEDFD9" box="[174,233,1667,1694]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[166,199,1438,1460]" captionTargetBox="[161,1221,206,1413]" captionTargetId="figure-106@2.[160,780,205,857]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Sucinoptinus from Rovno amber: 1 — Sucinoptinus rovnoensis sp. n. Holotype, SIZK UA-335; 2 — Sucinoptinus brevipennis sp.n. Holotype, SIZK D-2295; 3 — Sucinoptinus sp.? SIZK UA-284; 4 — Sucinoptinus sp.? SIZK K-6067; 5 — Sucinoptinus? sp.? SIZK K-25483; 6 — Rovno amber deposits with Sucinoptinus inclusions: a — Dubrovitsa, b — Klesov. Scale 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6414449" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6414449/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">fig. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<emphasis id="FAE0EACADC11FF16FF3518B7FE30DFD9" box="[249,263,1668,1694]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">2</emphasis>
). Head finely punctuated and pubescent; interantennal space narrow and rather flat; eyes hemispherical, quite prominent and finely faceted. Antennae eleven segmented, slender and long, slightly longer than the elytral length, covered with semierect pubescence; antennomere proportions according to the formula: 7–3–4–4–4–4–4–4–4.5–5–8.5 (
<figureCitation id="50AF2A5DDC11FF16FB4B18D0FBF5DFB9" box="[1159,1218,1763,1790]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[166,199,1438,1460]" captionTargetBox="[161,1221,206,1413]" captionTargetId="figure-106@2.[160,780,205,857]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Sucinoptinus from Rovno amber: 1 — Sucinoptinus rovnoensis sp. n. Holotype, SIZK UA-335; 2 — Sucinoptinus brevipennis sp.n. Holotype, SIZK D-2295; 3 — Sucinoptinus sp.? SIZK UA-284; 4 — Sucinoptinus sp.? SIZK K-6067; 5 — Sucinoptinus? sp.? SIZK K-25483; 6 — Rovno amber deposits with Sucinoptinus inclusions: a — Dubrovitsa, b — Klesov. Scale 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6414449" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6414449/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">fig. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<emphasis id="FAE0EACADC11FF16FF6A1937FF83DE59" box="[166,180,1796,1822]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="19">2</emphasis>
). Pronotum slightly longer than wide and wider than a single elytron; apical margin widely convex anteriorly, partially concealing the head; sides slightly rounded, only slightly constricted near the base, moderately convex at the disk and showing a quite apparent transversal depression in the posterior third; surface irregularly sculptured in the anterior third, with round, small tubercles in the disk, and with small elongated tubercles in the posterior third transversal depression; pubescence formed by short semi-recumbent hairs evenly distributed (
<figureCitation id="50AF2A5DDC10FF17FE171F1CFD2ED80E" box="[475,537,303,329]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[166,199,1438,1460]" captionTargetBox="[161,1221,206,1413]" captionTargetId="figure-106@2.[160,780,205,857]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Sucinoptinus from Rovno amber: 1 — Sucinoptinus rovnoensis sp. n. Holotype, SIZK UA-335; 2 — Sucinoptinus brevipennis sp.n. Holotype, SIZK D-2295; 3 — Sucinoptinus sp.? SIZK UA-284; 4 — Sucinoptinus sp.? SIZK K-6067; 5 — Sucinoptinus? sp.? SIZK K-25483; 6 — Rovno amber deposits with Sucinoptinus inclusions: a — Dubrovitsa, b — Klesov. Scale 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6414449" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6414449/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="20">fig. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<emphasis id="FAE0EACADC10FF17FDE51F1CFD00D80E" box="[553,567,303,329]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="20">2</emphasis>
). Legs short and robust covered with short recumbent pubescence; tarsi relatively long, nearly as long as tibiae; mesotarsi with tarsomere proportions according to the formula: 5–1.5–1.5–1–5. Scutellum triangular, as long as wide. Elytra subparallel and short, only slightly longer than twice the length of the pronotum; humeri prominent; elytral surface serially punctuated by elongated strial punctures, leaving an interstriae interval about twice wider as the width of the striae; pubescence formed by semirecumbent short setae inserted in the punctures (with a length similar to that of the puncture) and erect and moderately long (somewhat longer than those of the punctures) setae inserted in the intervals (
<figureCitation id="50AF2A5DDC10FF17FDDE1C1CFD7BDB0E" box="[530,588,559,585]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[166,199,1438,1460]" captionTargetBox="[161,1221,206,1413]" captionTargetId="figure-106@2.[160,780,205,857]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Sucinoptinus from Rovno amber: 1 — Sucinoptinus rovnoensis sp. n. Holotype, SIZK UA-335; 2 — Sucinoptinus brevipennis sp.n. Holotype, SIZK D-2295; 3 — Sucinoptinus sp.? SIZK UA-284; 4 — Sucinoptinus sp.? SIZK K-6067; 5 — Sucinoptinus? sp.? SIZK K-25483; 6 — Rovno amber deposits with Sucinoptinus inclusions: a — Dubrovitsa, b — Klesov. Scale 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6414449" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6414449/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="20">fig. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<emphasis id="FAE0EACADC10FF17FD961C1CFD5FDB0E" box="[602,616,559,585]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="20">2</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C82B36D8DC10FF17FF2F1C63FE73DA6E" blockId="3.[174,1233,175,874]" pageId="3" pageNumber="20">
D i a g n o s t i c c h a r a c t e r s. 
<taxonomicName id="0F944D5BDC10FF17FD941C63FC33DB2E" authorityName="Bellés &amp; Perkovsky" authorityYear="2016" box="[600,772,591,618]" class="Insecta" family="Ptinidae" genus="Sucinoptinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevipennis">
<emphasis id="FAE0EACADC10FF17FD941C63FC33DB2E" box="[600,772,591,618]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="20">S. brevipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to the previously known species, 
<taxonomicName id="0F944D5BDC10FF17FEC31C43FE49DBCE" authorityName="Alexeev" authorityYear="2012" box="[271,382,623,650]" class="Insecta" family="Ptinidae" genus="Sucinoptinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bukejsi">
<emphasis id="FAE0EACADC10FF17FEC31C43FE49DBCE" box="[271,382,623,650]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="20">S. bukejsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="0F944D5BDC10FF17FE741C43FD2EDBCE" box="[440,537,624,650]" class="Insecta" family="Ptinidae" genus="Sucinoptinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sucini">
<emphasis id="FAE0EACADC10FF17FE741C43FD2EDBCE" box="[440,537,624,650]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="20">S. sucini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having the same general structure of the prothorax, but differing from these species in having much shorter elytra, with a proportion length of the pronotum (LP)/length of the elytra (LE) = 2.1. This clearly differs from the proportion found in 
<taxonomicName id="0F944D5BDC10FF17FEEC1CE3FEB3DBAE" box="[288,388,720,746]" class="Insecta" family="Ptinidae" genus="Sucinoptinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sucini">
<emphasis id="FAE0EACADC10FF17FEEC1CE3FEB3DBAE" box="[288,388,720,746]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="20">S. sucini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(LE/LP = 2.7), in 
<taxonomicName id="0F944D5BDC10FF17FDA91CE3FDE1DBAE" authorityName="Alexeev" authorityYear="2012" box="[613,726,719,746]" class="Insecta" family="Ptinidae" genus="Sucinoptinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bukejsi">
<emphasis id="FAE0EACADC10FF17FDA91CE3FDE1DBAE" box="[613,726,719,746]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="20">S. bukejsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(LE/LP = 2.6, according to measurement made on the pictures sent by V. Alekseev) and in 
<taxonomicName id="0F944D5BDC10FF17FCC11CC3FC90DA4E" authorityName="Bellés &amp; Perkovsky" authorityYear="2016" box="[781,935,752,778]" class="Insecta" family="Ptinidae" genus="Sucinoptinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rovnoensis">
<emphasis id="FAE0EACADC10FF17FCC11CC3FC90DA4E" box="[781,935,752,778]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="20">S. rovnoensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, described above, where LE/LP = 3.0.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C82B36D8DC10FF17FF2F1D03FD01DA2E" blockId="3.[174,1233,175,874]" pageId="3" pageNumber="20">E t y m o l o g y. The specific name refers to the shortness of the elytra, which is the most typical feature of the new species.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
